### Swift Protocols

Protocols define a blueprint of methods, properties, and requirements that conforming types must implement. They are fundamental to Swift's protocol-oriented programming paradigm.

**Protocol Syntax:**

```swift
protocol ProtocolName {
    // Property requirements
    var readable: String { get }
    var readwrite: Int { get set }

    // Method requirements
    func method() -> ReturnType
    mutating func mutatingMethod()

    // Initializer requirements
    init(parameter: Type)
}
```

**Conforming to a Protocol:**

```swift
protocol Vehicle {
    var speed: Double { get set }
    func move() -> String
}

struct Car: Vehicle {
    var speed: Double = 0.0

    func move() -> String {
        return "Car moves at \(speed) km/h"
    }
}

struct Bicycle: Vehicle {
    var speed: Double = 0.0

    func move() -> String {
        return "Bicycle moves at \(speed) km/h"
    }
}
```

**Property Requirements:**

| Declaration | Meaning |
|-------------|---------|
| `{ get }` | At least readable (constant or variable) |
| `{ get set }` | Both readable and writable |
| `static var` | Type property requirement |

```swift
protocol Named {
    var name: String { get }
}

struct Person: Named {
    let name: String  // Satisfies { get }
}

struct MutablePerson: Named {
    var name: String  // Also satisfies { get }
}
```

**Protocol as Type:**

```swift
// Protocol used as a type
let vehicles: [Vehicle] = [Car(speed: 120), Bicycle(speed: 25)]

// Protocol as parameter
func race(vehicles: [Vehicle]) {
    for v in vehicles {
        print(v.move())
    }
}

// Protocol as return type
func createVehicle() -> Vehicle {
    return Car(speed: 100)
}
```

> **Key Point:** Protocols are types. You can use them as parameter types, return types, and in collections. This enables polymorphism without inheritance.

Classes, structs, and enums can all conform to protocols. A type can conform to multiple protocols:

```swift
struct MyType: ProtocolOne, ProtocolTwo {
    // Must implement all requirements
}
```

codeExample:
import Foundation

protocol Describable {
    var description: String { get }
    func describe() -> String
}

protocol Resettable {
    mutating func reset()
}

struct User: Describable, Resettable {
    var name: String
    var age: Int

    var description: String {
        "\(name), \(age) years old"
    }

    func describe() -> String {
        "User: \(description)"
    }

    mutating func reset() {
        name = ""
        age = 0
    }
}

var user = User(name: "Alice", age: 30)
print(user.describe())
user.reset()
print(user.describe())

// Protocol as type
func printDescriptions(_ items: [Describable]) {
    for item in items {
        print(item.describe())
    }
}

let items: [Describable] = [
    User(name: "Bob", age: 25),
    User(name: "Charlie", age: 35)
]
printDescriptions(items)
